Company description: LEONIDAS was founded in 1842, some 120 years later it merged with Heuer creating the largest manufacturer of stopwatches and chronographs in Switzerland, and establishing Heuer-Leonidas as one of the biggest and most influential watch brands in the world.  During the 80's the company came under increasing pressure to compete with the influx of cheaper quartz models from China. The brand‚Äôs reluctance to compromise quality over price saw Heuer-Leonidas become Tag-Heuer with Leonidas falling by the wayside.  It was in 2015 that Leonidas first tiptoed back into the watch making arena with the 5024, their first stand alone model since falling victim to the quartz crisis some 50 years earlier. Rather unsurprisingly upon their return Leonidas vowed never to use a movement powered by a battery.  The unorthodox positioning of the logo on the 5024 in the bottom half of the dial was no accident - it was in fact referencing the brand‚Äôs historic past when Heuer-Leonidas dominated the supply of timing devices to major sporting events. Due to the hand configuration on a stopwatch it‚Äôs not possible to place the logo in the traditional space. Instead it‚Äôs positioned above the nbr 30 marker (or 6 on a watch ). It's a nice touch to see it taking up the same position some 50 years later.  Leonidas don‚Äôt mass-produce their timepieces; with a Leonidas watch exclusivity of wear is dictated by the availability of the range rather than the ticket price. ‚ÄòWe don‚Äôt claim to be an exclusive brand on one hand whilst simultaneously manufacturing  3000 watches a day on the other‚Äô says Matthews (the current owner and CEO of the brand).

Company description: Hopstay is an Australian-founded smart city startup currently based in Paris and is a laureate of the French Tech Ticket program, a prestigious French government-funded program for international startups. Hopstay's solution helps cities optimise customer support & improve urban experience through smart digital assistants (chatbots & voicebots). Cities use our framework to more efficiently process complaints, queries & tasks that are otherwise painful & tedious for citizens. There are 3 key elements to the Hopstay technology framework. 1. Knowledge base & bot management platform A platform where city bodies can manage their knowledge database, chatbot functionality, push notifications and view analytics and data. The platform integrates both proprietary content (provided by the client) and also urban data sets from open data platforms.  2. Pre-built citizen service modules A library of common city/local government processes that have been pre-coded & designed for the conversational interface. For example, reporting an issue, checking waste collection status, finding parking, viewing road conditions. This library of ‚Äòplug & play‚Äô modules seamlessly connect to both the backend system of the client & popular customer support platforms (such as live chat). 3. Centralised natural language processing library We centralise our training data as part of our commitment to building the world's largest natural language processing library for cities. By focusing on a specific type of interaction (city-citizen), we can share training data which enables us to improve chatbot intent recognition at an exponential rate. The result is smarter chatbots in shorter time periods. Hopstay works with a portfolio of clients across Australia, Europe & North America.
